\subsection{Existence of Reactive Energy in (Real) Time}\label{sec:TVphasor}

The real part of (\ref{eq:S_RLC}) gives $P=P_d$, as known from (\ref{eq:Pdaverage}). However, there is no such balance equation for the imaginary part of (\ref{eq:S_RLC}) in terms of a (rate of change of) reactive energy in time. The obstacle here is that the imaginary part is not integrable with respect to the voltage and current phasors, and therefore does not allow for a potential function that can be associated to reactive energy. This fact  was proved in \cite{Carozzi2005} in the context of electromagnetic fields. 


